# Signals — the kernel's notifications

A **signal** is a small message the kernel delivers to a process (number + name). The process can **default** (usually terminate), **catch** it, **ignore**, or **block** it.

## Two the kernel enforces — uncatchable

- **`SIGKILL` (9)** — die now, no cleanup. Last resort.
- **`SIGSTOP` (19)** — pause now. Resume with `SIGCONT`.

## The handful you'll use  (`kill -l` lists all)

| Signal | № | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| **`SIGTERM`** | 15 | **polite shutdown** — `kill`'s default, catchable |
| **`SIGKILL`** | 9 | **last resort** — instant, no cleanup |
| **`SIGINT`** | 2 | **Ctrl-C** — interactive interrupt |
| **`SIGHUP`** | 1 | daemons: **"reload your config"** |
| **`SIGTSTP`/`CONT`** | 20/18 | **Ctrl-Z** pause / resume |

The three you'll send: **`TERM`** ask nicely · **`KILL`** when ignored · **`HUP`** reload config.
